Using cross validation to determine optimal lambda values

set.seed(1)
Facebook$partition <- sample(
  x = c("train", "test"),
  size = nrow(Facebook),
  replace = TRUE,
  prob = c(0.85,0.15)
)

v_predictors <- names(Facebook)[c(1:18,22:49)]

cv.ridge <- glmnet::cv.glmnet(
  x = Facebook[,v_predictors] %>%
    dplyr::filter(Facebook$partition == "train") %>%
    as.matrix(),
  y = Facebook$YJ.total.interactions[Facebook$partition == "train"],
  alpha = 0
)
cv.ridge
## 
## Call:  glmnet::cv.glmnet(x = Facebook[, v_predictors] %>% dplyr::filter(Facebook$partition ==      "train") %>% as.matrix(), y = Facebook$YJ.total.interactions[Facebook$partition ==      "train"], alpha = 0) 
## 
## Measure: Mean-Squared Error 
## 
##     Lambda Index Measure     SE Nonzero
## min  0.229   100   0.142 0.0451      45
## 1se  0.332    96   0.177 0.0474      45

The minimum penalty lambda = 0.229 and the largest lambda within 1 standard error of the minimum = 0.332. We will go with lambda = 0.332 for ridge. The following plot shows that we are gaining more by using a higher lambda value without before being significantly affected by greater error.

plot(
  x = cv.ridge
)

cv.lasso <- glmnet::cv.glmnet(

This gives us a better model in this case because the selected variables make more sense from a subject point of view.

Comparing performance on test set

Earlier, the %Dev for ridge, lasso, and elastic net were: 97.2%, 98.2%, 98.3% respectively

ridge <- glmnet::glmnet(
  x = Facebook[,v_predictors] %>%
    dplyr::filter(Facebook$partition == "test") %>%
    as.matrix(),
  y = Facebook$YJ.total.interactions[Facebook$partition == "test"],
  alpha = 0,
  lambda = 0.3321
)

## Call:  glmnet::glmnet(x = Facebook[, v_predictors] %>% dplyr::filter(Facebook$partition ==      "test") %>% as.matrix(), y = Facebook$YJ.total.interactions[Facebook$partition ==      "test"], alpha = 0.5, lambda = 0.21249) 
## 
##   Df %Dev Lambda
## 1  6 98.6  0.212

The %Dev increased to 98.6%.

For all 3 models, the %Dev increased slightly meaning the % of deviance explained by the model indicates a slight better fit. Normally, the training statistics are supposed to be better than the test statistics so this does raise some concerns. However, since both statistics are tight, this is an indicator that all 3 models generalize well on unknown data. Out of all 3 methods, lasso performed the best because the difference between the training and test statistics was the smallest indicating this model had the best generalization.

In the real world, feature selection can reduce cost and minimize overfitting. We would prefer lasso over ridge when we need to perform feature selection since the penalty assigns a 0 to variables essentially eliminating the variable. We would prefer ridge over lasso when all variables need to be present in the model for legal reasons.
